# Interactive Workshop Template (Spectacle)

## Format: Variable length | Framework: Spectacle (React) | Duration: 1-4 hours

---

## Why Spectacle for Workshops

Workshops need interactive elements: live code editors, embedded exercises, timers, and dynamic content. Spectacle's React component model lets you build custom slide types (exercise cards, timer slides, poll embeds) that static frameworks cannot match.

---

## Narrative Arc

Workshops alternate between **teaching** and **doing**. The rhythm is:

1. Concept introduction (3-5 min)
2. Demonstration (5-10 min)
3. Hands-on exercise (10-20 min)
4. Group review (5 min)
5. Repeat

Build in breaks every 45-60 minutes.

---

## Slide Types

### Title Card

```jsx
<Slide backgroundColor="primary">
  <FlexBox height="100%" flexDirection="column" justifyContent="center" alignItems="center">
    <Heading fontSize="h1" color="tertiary">[Workshop Title]</Heading>
    <Text fontSize="h3" color="tertiary">[Your Name] | [Date]</Text>
    <Text fontSize="text" color="tertiary" marginTop={40}>
      WiFi: [network] | Password: [password]
    </Text>
    <Text fontSize="text" color="tertiary">
      Repo: [github-url]
    </Text>
  </FlexBox>
  <Notes>
    Welcome everyone. Before we start, make sure you have:
    1. Cloned the repo
    2. Run npm install
    3. Connected to WiFi
    Give them 5 minutes to set up.
  </Notes>
</Slide>
```

---

### Setup Check Slide

```jsx
<Slide>
  <Heading>Before We Begin</Heading>
  <OrderedList>
    <Appear><ListItem>Clone the repo: <code>[url]</code></ListItem></Appear>
    <Appear><ListItem>Run <code>npm install</code></ListItem></Appear>
    <Appear><ListItem>Run <code>npm run verify</code> -- you should see "Ready"</ListItem></Appear>
    <Appear><ListItem>Open <code>exercises/</code> in your editor</ListItem></Appear>
  </OrderedList>
  <Notes>
    Walk around the room. Help anyone who is stuck. Do not proceed until
    80% of the room has a working setup. Common issues: Node version,
    npm permissions, corporate proxy.
  </Notes>
</Slide>
```

---

### Concept Slide

```jsx
<Slide>
  <Heading>[Concept Name]</Heading>
  <Text>[One paragraph explanation]</Text>
  <Appear>
    <Text fontWeight="bold" color="secondary">
      Key insight: [the one thing to remember]
    </Text>
  </Appear>
  <Notes>
    Explain the concept in plain language first. Use an analogy if helpful.
    Then reveal the key insight. This is what they need to hold in their
    head during the exercise.
  </Notes>
</Slide>
```

---

### Live Code Slide

```jsx
<Slide>
  <Heading fontSize="h3">[What this code demonstrates]</Heading>
  <CodePane language="javascript" highlightRanges={[1, [3, 5], [7, 10]]}>
{`// Step 1: [What we're setting up]
const client = createClient({ apiKey: process.env.KEY });

// Step 2: [The key operation]
const result = await client.query({
  collection: 'users',
  filter: { active: true },
});

// Step 3: [Processing the result]
const formatted = result.map(user => ({
  name: user.displayName,
  email: user.primaryEmail,
}));`}
  </CodePane>
  <Notes>
    Type this live if you can. If not, step through the highlights.
    "First we create the client... then we make our query... then we
    process the results." Ask the room: "What would happen if we
    removed the filter?"
  </Notes>
</Slide>
```

